{
  "comment_text": {
    "snp1.6:2.1": "Several of the examples are gendered so I use “man”. ",
    "snp1.6:2.3": "Accept variant <i lang='pi' translate='no'>bhavantaṁ</i> in this and similar passages. <i lang='pi' translate='no'>Bhagavantaṁ</i> is hypermetrical. ",
    "snp1.6:2.4": "",
    "snp1.6:3.1": "For “easy to understand” (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>suvijāna</i>) cf. Rig Veda 7.104.12 and <i lang='pi' translate='no'>durvijñāna</i> at Śatapatha Brāhmaṇa 11.5.5.13. ",
    "snp1.6:3.3": "<i lang='pi' translate='no'>Dhammakāmo</i> is apparently always used in this sense. ",
    "snp1.6:19.2": "Both Norman and Bodhi read <i lang='pi' translate='no'>dissati</i>, I read <i lang='pi' translate='no'>dussati</i>. The Buddha, after all, was “seen” with prostitutes. "
  },
